Fixed comments from Zack.

@madjam - Can we get this reviewed and merged?

Thanks

@nikrao , yes, according to the documentation, in forward pass, this layers only computes the softmax output of previous layer (i.e., a normalized probability distribution). 
During training, the cross entropy loss is computed by combining this info and the ground truth label info.
See [here](http://mxnet.io/tutorials/python/mnist.html#) for a complete example on how to train a MLP or CNN  on the minist dataset using `mx.sym.SoftmaxOutput` as loss function.

@sxjscience  Alright.  The way to handle weight decay seems to be not important in many experiments. 

@leezu  But the way to handle 'clip_gradient' is wrong.   
https://github.com/dmlc/mxnet/blob/master/src/operator/optimizer_op-inl.h#L317

What implemented here is weight clipping,  which should not be activated in 'clip_gradient'.

@alanhuang1990 It's the check that decides whether to turn on weight clipping.
```c++
if (param.clip_weights >= 0.0f) {
   Assign(out, req[0], F<clip>(weight + delta, DType(param.clip_weights)));
}
```
